@G[c3 stills_129.png]@L 
        @H Historical Background @L
        Tarsus had been settled for over 6,000 years starting with the Hittites during the Bronze Age. The city played a key role as a trade hub for many of its former owners and was a point of contention during the times of Alexander and would continue to be a highly sought-after prize to control for many future cultures. @L@L
        In the year 67 BC, Pompey Magnus defeated Cilician pirates and in one of his most brilliant strategic, military, and political moves annexed the whole region into the Roman Republic. For this he received a triumph and was celebrated for years to come even though, as previously mentioned, he still failed politically to have the claims recognized quickly. @L@L
        There is no doubt that Pompey was a very competent strategic thinker. The Cilician pirates operated from small bases mostly on the Aegean and Dalmatian coasts and islands, as well as in Asia Minor. These pirates would prey upon Roman merchant ships and kidnap to extort rich Romans. During his young age, Caesar once found himself kidnapped by the pirates (since the story is widely known, I will refrain from going over it here). @L@L
        Before Pompey was given the job to pacify the area, his predecessor, asked for years to achieve this task, was given a large naval force and immense amounts of money was spent. Unfortunately, this did not lead to any developments, as raiding a pirate base would see them flee to only establish themselves elsewhere. Large and cumbersome maneuvers were easily evaded by small groups of raiding ships. @L@L
        Pompey took the task on and in mere weeks managed to achieve what others could not do in years, done all with smaller forces. Surprise was achieved by landing marines some distance away and attacking the pirates from land while blockading them from fleeing with ships at the same time was preferable. @L@L
        Surrender was accepted and pirates granted mercy under condition that they would be resettled elsewhere. This broke down the piratical local cultural ties and safeguarded the Roman vital sea lanes for trade and transport. @L@L

		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]
        @H Instructions @L
        Governor, travel to Cilicia. Your new assignment is the Romanization of the city of Tarsus. It is to become a capital of the new province of Cilicia, and it will fall onto your shoulders to make it into a truly great city in the Roman east. On the details of the assignment, it might prove the most challenging thus far. @L@L
        First, the good. The area around the city is rich in all manner of ores, metals, and precious stones. Extracting them might prove difficult but it will be the foundation of the economy in Tarsus. Unfortunately, Tarsus has no farmland to speak of or deposits of clay. Local trees are also not suitable for use as timber for most projects. This leaves the city in a precarious position. It will be vital to establish a wide-ranging trade network and manage the many imports and exports that pass through your city. @L@L 
		If that was not enough, we are also still struggling to convince the Greeks that the Roman faith and pantheon are superior to their own. To demonstrate the superiority of Roman gods, your city will only be able to construct a few small shrines initially. Instead, as the city grows, construct immense monuments to the glory of Rome and her gods. @L@L
		As for military matters, the Parthians are testing our defenses, and you can expect raids into our territory to be frequent. Fortunately for us, these barbarians know nothing about proper warfare and as long as you keep at least several garrisoned legions, you should not need to worry too much about their activities. @L@L@L

        @H Edicts @L
        @Cultural @Tensions - Your city is only allowed to build 10 small temples of any kind. After they have been built, they get disabled and if you exceed this limit by using exploits, you will lose favor and denarii rapidly. @L@L
        @Mining @Magnate - The map has all mining resources available. The first mine of each kind will generate +1 resources every 2 months directly into stockpiles. @L@L

		@H Additional Information @L
		There are 2 invasion points on the map, and it has some military activity. Mining spots are marked with circular road patterns on the map - look for mining spots in the mountains. This map has been changed more than some of the others, since in the base game it's so flat and boring that it was not worth keeping most of its "features." @L@L
        This map will try to teach you that you do not have to go for all grand insula housing for plebs. When a second food type is rare, it's acceptable to keep them lower and compensate by using more or higher evolved patrician housing instead. With a full highway, caravanserai, and/or Grand Temple to Mercury bonuses, you can still manage to have all plebian housing evolved up to grand insula. @L@L
        @H Persistent Events @L
        Grand Temple to Mercury unlocks plaza. Subsidy lasts until 10 prosperity is achieved and gives 100 dn. monthly until it expires. Workshops only unlock after the subsidy expires. @L@L
        Due to game limitations, starting prices for goods will be adjusted after 1 in-game month has passed. @L@L@L@L@L

