		@H Historical Background @L
        At this time, Egypt has been indebted to the Roman Republic and effectively turned into a client state. This did not mean direct Roman control however; Egypt would still be ruled directly by the Ptolemaic dynasty, named after Ptolemy, who was one of Alexander the Great's commanders and founder of the dynasty. @L@L
        Egypt, after Alexander's conquest, was a hybrid society of natives and Greek and Macedonian immigrants, where the pharaoh would be merged with kingly titles, and armies and society reflected the new rulers by embracing new traditions, organization and economics. During this time, Egypt was again in heavy decline, however, and was completely annexed at the end of the final civil war. @L@L
        Even though it was in decline, Egypt would continue to produce much of the wheat that was used to fill up Roman granaries and supplement the grain dole for the urban poor. @L@L@L@L

